Introduction
MRI is often the imaging modality of choice for noninvasive
characterization of brain anatomy because of its excellent soft tissue
contrast. Its detailed resolution allows the investigation of normal
anatomical variability bounds, as well as the quantization of
volumetric changes accompanying neurological conditions. A prerequisite for such studies is an accurate segmentation of the brain;
therefore, many studies have focused on tissue classiÔ¨Åcation into
white matter, gray matter and cerebrospinal Ô¨Çuid (CSF), as well as
anatomical structure segmentation. Several successful methods for
tissue segmentation include statistical classiÔ¨Åcation and geometrydriven segmentation (Ballester et al., 2000), statistical pattern
recognition methods based on a Ô¨Ånite mixture model (Andersen et
al., 2002), expectation maximization algorithm (Kovacevic et al.,
2002), artiÔ¨Åcial neural network (Reddick et al., 1997), hidden Markov
random Ô¨Åeld (Zhang et al., 2001), and region-based level-set and
fuzzy classiÔ¨Åcation (Suri, 2001). Compared to anatomical structure

