Conclusions

With the tag-weighted topic model proposed in the paper, we
provide and analyze a probabilistic approach for mining semistructured documents. This model provides signiÔ¨Åcantly improved predictive capability in terms of perplexity compared
to the other topic models, such as LDA and CTM. Besides,
TWTM was shown to be able to obtain the topics distribution
of tags in the corpus, which is very useful for text classiÔ¨Åcation, clustering and other data mining applications. Meanwhile, TWTM proposes a novel framework of processing the
tagged text with a high extensibility, and uses a novel function
of tag-weighted topic assignment of documents. The primary
beneÔ¨Åt of the tag-weighted topic model is that it allows one
to incorporate diÔ¨Äerent types of tags in modeling documents,
and provides a general framework for multi-tags modeling at
not only the level of tags but also the level of documents. It
helps provide diÔ¨Äerent approaches in classiÔ¨Åcation, clustering, recommendation, and so on. In the future, we plan to
apply TWTM to diÔ¨Äerent practical areas, especially the problems of the large-scale document modeling.

Figure 5 shows that the topic we selected has the diÔ¨Äerent
value between the tags, the 31 days. The results shows that at
the label of ‚ÄúMar. 11‚Äù the value reaches maximum and there
