Lee‚Äô are likely to be same names, even though ‚ÄòBenjamin‚Äô
differ from ‚ÄòB‚Äô with the extra suffix ‚Äòenjamin‚Äô. Both JaroWinkler distance and LCP will consider ‚ÄòB‚Äô and ‚ÄòBenjamin‚Äô
are similar, because they do not count too much on suffixes.
But other common similarity functions, such as Levenshtein
distance4 , would severely affected by suffix ‚Äòenjamin‚Äô and do
not consider ‚ÄòB‚Äô and ‚ÄòBenjamin‚Äô are similar.
We use bipartite graph to deal with irregular name format. For example, ‚ÄòBenjamin Lee‚Äô maybe written as ‚ÄòLee
Benjamin M.‚Äô. We want the word ‚ÄòBenjamin‚Äô and ‚ÄòLee‚Äô in
both names matched regardless of order and the extra word
‚ÄòM.‚Äô, so that we can judge these two names are similar. We
can split the first name into 2 words ‚ÄòBenjamin‚Äô and ‚ÄòLee‚Äô,
assuming their indices are 1 and 2. Similarly we can split
the second name into 3 words ‚ÄòLee‚Äô, ‚ÄòBenjamin‚Äô and ‚ÄòM.‚Äô, assuming their indices are 3, 4 and 5. Then we construct the
bipartite graph by adding edges between the two word sets,
setting the weight of the edges to be similarities calculated
by LCP or Jaro-Winkler distance. So the edge connecting
word 1 (‚ÄòBenjamin‚Äô in first name) and word 4 (‚ÄòBenjamin‚Äô in
second name) is weighted high. Similarly the edge connecting word 2 (‚ÄòLee‚Äô in first name) and word 3 (‚ÄòLee‚Äô in second
name) is also weighted high. But other edges, such as the
one connecting word 1 and word 5 (‚ÄòM.‚Äô in second name)
is weighted low. After running maximum weighted bipartite matching we can correctly find the high-weighted edges
illustrated above and consider the two names are similar.
After using similarity functions focusing on prefix to build
bipartite graph, we can calculate the similarity of names
more precisely. Our model will consider ‚ÄòBenjamin Lee‚Äô and
‚ÄòB. M. Lee‚Äô are similar, but ‚ÄòBenjamin Lee‚Äô and ‚ÄòM. Lee‚Äô will
still not be considered similar.
