To achieve these goals, we propose an algorithm called Approximate Fair Dropping (AFD). AFD uses a FIFO queue
with probabilistic drop-on-arrival. These probabilistic dropping decisions are based not only on the past measurements
of the queue size but also on the recent history of a Ô¨Çow.3
AFD uses the history to estimate the Ô¨Çow‚Äôs current sending
rate, and then drops with a probability designed to limit
that Ô¨Çow‚Äôs throughput to the fair share. Thus, dropping
is not applied uniformly across Ô¨Çows (as in RED) but is
applied diÔ¨Äerentially based on an estimate of the Ô¨Çow‚Äôs current sending rate. The exact form of diÔ¨Äerential dropping is
chosen to approximate fair bandwidth allocations.

The second contribution of AFD lies in its technical novelty.
While several components of its design are present in existing algorithms, it is the Ô¨Årst algorithm to leverage the distribution of Ô¨Çow rates in conjunction with per-packet sampling
in order to address the scalability requirements of per-Ô¨Çow
state. By basing the design of AFD on this characteristic
of network traÔ¨Éc, we have achieved an important advance
in this class of algorithms. Furthermore, we demonstrate
techniques that reduce AFD‚Äôs complexity relative to other
algorithms while not sacriÔ¨Åcing performance.

Our design might initially appear to be seriously misguided.
The state required to keep enough history to accurately estimate each Ô¨Çow‚Äôs rate is quite large, and grows linearly with
the number of Ô¨Çows. This is clearly not a feasible approach.
However, note that our design only needs to estimate the
rates of Ô¨Çows whose packets are likely to be dropped. Thus,
we need only keep enough state to estimate rates when those
rates are comparable to (or larger than) the fair share rate.
This is a crucial diÔ¨Äerence.

This paper has 7 sections. We describe a conceptual version
of our design in Section 2, and then use analysis to develop
guidelines for the various parameters in Section 3. We then
present the practical design in Section 4. We evaluate this
design using simulation in Section 5, and use trace data and
other measurements to estimate the state requirements for
the design in Section 6. We conclude in Section 7 with a
discussion of related work.

It is well known that the distribution of the sizes of Ô¨Çows (the
total number of bytes transferred) has a long tail, and that
most Ô¨Çows are small ‚Äì the mice ‚Äì but a large fraction of the
bytes are sent by large Ô¨Çows ‚Äì the elephants.4 As we show
using trace data in Section 6, and has been observed in [14],
the distribution of Ô¨Çow rates has a similar property. While
perhaps not as long-tailed as the size distribution, initial
evidence suggests that the Ô¨Çow rate distribution (measured
on the time scale of a second) is long-tailed. Most Ô¨Çows are
slow (in bits/sec) ‚Äì we will call them turtles ‚Äì but most of
the bytes are sent by fast Ô¨Çows ‚Äì we will call them cheetahs.

