Congestion control is one of the Internet‚Äôs most fundamental
architectural problems. In the current Internet, most routers
do not actively manage per-Ô¨Çow bandwidth allocations, and
so the bandwidth received by a Ô¨Çow depends on the congestion control algorithms used by other competing Ô¨Çows. To
achieve relatively equitable bandwidth allocations, all Ô¨Çows
must be TCP-compatible [4] (also known as TCP-friendly);
that is, they must use a congestion control algorithm that
results in bandwidth allocations similar to TCP‚Äôs. This approach requires uniformity and cooperation, both of which
might be problematic.

