In literature, Nelson [1] described a degradation model and the
statistical method for analyzing age-degradation data on product
performance. Meeker and Hamada [2] presented a conceptual
degradation-based reliability model to describe the role of, and
need for, integration of reliability data sources. Meeker and
Escobar [3] applied the Arrhenius acceleration model on the
ADT analysis. Bae et al. [4] investigated the link between a
practitioner‚Äôs selected degradation model and the resulting lifetime model. Lu [5] assumed that the degradation process follows
a Wiener process, so the Ô¨Årst passage time distribution to a
barrier is distributed as an inverse Gaussian distribution. Pettit
and Young [6] extended the analysis in Lu by using a fully
Bayesian approach to model estimation and prediction. Barker
and Newby [7] addressed the problem of determining inspection
and maintenance strategy for a system whose state is described
by a multivariate Wiener process. Carey and Koenig [8], Tseng and
Yu [9], Tseng et al. [10] and Onar and Padgett [11,12] presented
their relevant methods of ADT based on Ô¨Ålm resistance, MOS,
logic chip, LED, carbolic Ô¨Åber, respectively.
Unlike the Ô¨Åeld-use condition, the stresses applied on the test
units in a laboratory testing condition can be precisely controlled,
so the extrapolated result from an ADT may not accurately
represent the real situation in the Ô¨Åeld, where most stress
variables are in fact random. To solve this problem, Liao and
Elsayed [13] extended an ADT model obtained from constantstress ADT experiments to predict Ô¨Åeld reliability by considering
the Ô¨Åeld stress variations. Meeker et al. [14] developed a use rate
model to relate ALT data and Ô¨Åeld data. Monroe and Pan [15]
made an effort of using global climate data to adjust the acceleration factor for any speciÔ¨Åc market place of electronic products.
However, it is difÔ¨Åcult to predict all stresses and stress variations
that the product will experience under its Ô¨Åeld condition. Integrating reliability information from various sources is crucial to
the solution and Bayesian data analysis provides a feasible means
for information fusion. In a series of paper by Hamada and his
colleagues [16‚Äì18] the methods of using hierarchical Bayes model
to integrate reliability information were investigated. Touw [19]
studied the Bayesian estimation of mixed Weibull distribution
and others. Pan [20] introduced a calibration factor to lifetime
model to make a more accurate prediction of Ô¨Åeld failure time by
considering the data from both ALT and Ô¨Åeld. This calibration
factor statistically calibrates the ALT model‚Äôs parameter and
prediction result without explicitly considering speciÔ¨Åc stress or
inÔ¨Çuencing factors. In this paper we formulate calibration factors
for the ADT model and use Bayesian methods to integrate ADT
and Ô¨Åeld data for reliability prediction.

